question_text: Who amongst the following had called Rabindranath Tagore as THE GREAT SENTINEL?
explanation: Mahatma Gandhi amongst the following had called Rabindranath Tagore as THE GREAT SENTINEL. Rabindranath Tagore was a key figure of the Bengal Renaissance. He started writing at an early age and by the turn of the century had become a household name in Bengal as a poet, a songwriter, a playwright, an essayist, a short story writer and a novelist. In 1913 he was awarded the Nobel Prize for Literature and his verse collection Gitanjali came to be known internationally. At about the same time he founded Visva-Bharati, a university located in Santiniketan, near Kolkata. Called the ‘Great Sentinel’ of modern India by Mahatma Gandhi, Tagore steered clear of active politics but is famous for returning his knighthood as a gesture of protest against the Jallianwala Bagh massacre in 1919.

question_text: Grand Central Terminal, Park Avenue, New York is the world's
explanation: Grand Central Terminal, Park Avenue, New York is the world's largest railway station. GCT is the largest train station in the world in terms of area occupied and number of platforms. The terminal is spread over 49 acres and has 44 platforms.

question_text: Entomology is the science that studies
option_A: The origin and history of technical and scientific terms
explanation: Entomology is the science that studies insects. Entomologists have many important jobs, such as the study of the classification, life cycle, distribution, physiology, behavior, ecology and population dynamics of insects.

question_text: Eritrea, which became the 182nd member of the UN in 1993, is in the continent of
explanation: Eritrea is a northeast African country on the Red Sea coast. It shares borders with Ethiopia, Sudan and Djibouti. The capital city, Asmara, is known for its Italian colonial buildings, like St. Joseph's Cathedral, as well as art deco structures. Italian, Egyptian and Turkish architecture in Massawa reflect the port city's colorful history. Notable buildings here include St. Mariam Cathedral and the Imperial Palace.

question_text: Garampani sanctuary is located at
explanation: Garampani sanctuary is located at Diphu, Assam. It is one of the oldest sanctuaries containing hot water spring and waterfalls and surrounded by Nambor Sanctuary having 51 rare species of orchid.

question_text: For which of the following disciplines is Nobel Prize awarded?
explanation: For Literature, Peace and Economics, Physics and Chemistry and Physiology or Medicine of the following disciplines the Nobel Prize is awarded.

question_text: Hitler party which came into power in 1933 is known as
explanation: Hitler party which came into power in 1933 is known as Nazi Party. Under the leadership of Adolf Hitler (1889-1945), the National Socialist German Workers’ Party, or Nazi Party, grew into a mass movement and ruled Germany through totalitarian means from 1933 to 1945. Founded in 1919 as the German Workers’ Party, the group promoted German pride and anti-Semitism, and expressed dissatisfaction with the terms of the Treaty of Versailles, the 1919 peace settlement that ended World War I (1914-1918) and required Germany to make numerous concessions and reparations.

question_text: FFC stands for
explanation: FFC stands for Film Finance Corporation. FFC, is India's state funding body for films. The 1927 Indian Cinematograph Committee recommended such a state-sponsored agency in its Report of the Indian Cinematograph Committee.

question_text: Fastest shorthand writer was
explanation: Fastest shorthand writer was Dr. G. D. Bist.

question_text: Epsom (England) is the place associated with
explanation: Epsom (England) is the place associated with Horse racing. Epsom is a market town in Surrey, England, 22.0 km south-west of London. Epsom Downs Racecourse holds The Derby, now a generic name for sports competitions in English-speaking countries. The town also gives its name to Epsom salts, extracted from mineral waters there.

question_text: First human heart transplant operation conducted by Dr. Christian Bernard on Louis Washkansky, was conducted in
explanation: Louis Washkansky (1913 - 21 December 1967) was the recipient of the world's first human heart transplant.Washkansky died of double pneumonia eighteen days after the transplant because of a weakened immune system.

question_text: Galileo was an Italian astronomer who
option_C: discovered that the movement of pendulum produces a regular time measurement
explanation: Galileo was an Italian astronomer who developed the telescope, discovered four satellites of Jupiter and discovered that the movement of pendulum produces a regular time measurement. Galileo was an Italian astronomer, mathematician, physicist, philosopher and professor who made pioneering observations of nature with long-lasting implications for the study of physics. He also constructed a telescope and supported the Copernican theory, which supports a sun-centered solar system.

question_text: Habeas Corpus Act 1679
option_A: provided facilities to a prisoner to obtain either speedy trial or release in bail
option_B: states that no one was to be imprisoned without a writ or warrant stating the charge against him
option_C: safeguarded the personal liberties of the people against arbitrary imprisonment by the king's orders
explanation: Habeas Corpus Act 1679 provided facilities to a prisoner to obtain either speedy trial or release in bail, states that no one was to be imprisoned without a writ or warrant stating the charge against him and safeguarded the personal liberties of the people against arbitrary imprisonment by the king's orders.

question_text: Exposure to sunlight helps a person improve his health because
option_B: the infrared light kills bacteria in the body
option_C: the ultraviolet rays convert skin oil into Vitamin D
option_D: the pigment cells in the skin get stimulated and produce a healthy tan
answer: the ultraviolet rays convert skin oil into Vitamin D
explanation: Exposure to sunlight helps a person improve his health because the ultraviolet rays convert skin oil into Vitamin D.

question_text: Golf player Vijay Singh belongs to which country?
explanation: Golf player Vijay Singh belongs to Fiji. He was born in 1963, who was number 1 in the Official World Golf Ranking for 32 weeks in 2004 and 2005. He was nicknamed as "The Big Fijian", has won three major Golf Championships.

question_text: Guarantee to an exporter that the importer of his goods will pay immediately for the goods ordered by him, is known as
explanation: Guarantee to an exporter that the importer of his goods will pay immediately for the goods ordered by him, is known as Letter of Credit (L/C). A Letter of Credit, also known as LC or Documentary Credit, is a commonly used instrument for effecting payment between a buyer and a seller. It can be a vital part of mitigating a seller's risk of payment in either international trade or domestic business.

question_text: First Afghan War took place in
explanation: First Afghan War took place in 1839. The First Anglo-Afghan War (also known by the British as the Disaster in Afghanistan) was fought between the British East India Company and the Emirate of Afghanistan from 1839 to 1842.

question_text: Gulf cooperation council was originally formed by
option_A: Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and United Arab Emirates
answer: Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and United Arab Emirates
explanation: Gulf cooperation council was created on May 25, 1981, the 630-million-acre (2,500,000 km2) Council comprises the Persian Gulf states of Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates.The unified economic agreement between the countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council was signed on November 11, 1981 in Abu Dhabi. These countries are often referred to as The GCC States.

question_text: First China War was fought between
explanation: First China War was fought between China and Britain. It was fought from 1839 - 42. It is also known as first Opium war.

question_text: Dumping is
option_A: selling of goods abroad at a price well below the production cost at the home market price
option_B: the process by which the supply of a manufacture's product remains low in the domestic market, which
answer: selling of goods abroad at a price well below the production cost at the home market price
explanation: Dumping is a term that is used in financial markets as well as in international trade. In the context of buying and selling securities, dumping refers to the practice of selling large blocks of securities. More specifically, when dumping securities the seller is primarily interested in getting rid of the securities at any price. One simply dumps, or unloads, on the market with no regard to the selling price of the securities.

question_text: For the Olympics and World Tournaments, the dimensions of basketball court are
explanation: For the Olympics and World Tournaments, the dimensions of basketball court are 28 m x 15 m.

question_text: Federation Cup, World Cup, Allywyn International Trophy and Challenge Cup are awarded to winners of
explanation: Federation Cup, World Cup, Allywyn International Trophy and Challenge Cup are awarded to winners of Volleyball.

question_text: Each year World Red Cross and Red Crescent Day is celebrated on
explanation: Each year World Red Cross and Red Crescent Day is celebrated on May 8. This date is the anniversary of the birth of Henry Dunant, who was born on 8 May 1828.

question_text: Famous sculptures depicting art of love built some time in 950 AD - 1050 AD are
explanation: Famous sculptures depicting art of love built some time in 950 AD - 1050 AD are Khajuraho temples. The Khajuraho Group of Monuments is a group of Hindu temples and Jain temples in Chhatarpur district, Madhya Pradesh, India, about 175 kilometres southeast of Jhansi. They are a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The temples are famous for their nagara-style architectural symbolism and their erotic sculptures.

question_text: Gravity setting chambers are used in industries to remove
explanation: Gravity setting chambers are used in industries to remove suspended particulate matter. A Gravitational Settling Chamber is a rectangular chamber in which several horizontal trays are fixed. When the polluted gas enters the chamber, its velocity is kept low so that the particulates get sufficient time to settle down due to gravity.

question_text: Guwahati High Court is the judicature of
explanation: Guwahati High Court is the judicature of Assam, Nagaland and Arunachal Pradesh.

question_text: Friction can be reduced by changing from
explanation: Friction can be reduced by changing from sliding to rolling. Replace sliding friction with rolling element friction, such as with the use of rolling element bearings.

question_text: During eleventh Antarctic Expedition in Nov. 1991/March 1992 ____ was installed.
explanation: SODAR (Sonic Detection And Ranging), also written as sodar, is a meteorological instrument also known as a wind profiler which measures the scattering of sound waves by atmospheric turbulence.

question_text: From the following, choose the set in which names of Secretary-Generals of the UNO are arranged in correct chronological order?
option_A: Trygve Lie, Dag Hammarskjoeld, U Thant, Kurt Waldheim.
option_B: U Thant, Dag Hammarskjoeld, Trygve Lie, Kurt Waldheim.

question_text: Fire temple is the place of worship of which of the following religion?
explanation: Fire temple is the place of worship of Zoroastrianism (Parsi Religion). A fire temple in Zoroastrianism is the place of worship for Zoroastrians, often called dar-e mehr (Persian) or agiyari (Gujarati). In the Zoroastrian religion, fire (see atar), together with clean water (see aban), are agents of ritual purity.

question_text: Film and TV institute of India is located at
explanation: Film and TV institute of India is located at Pune (Maharashtra). The Film and Television Institute of India (FTII) is an autonomous institute under the Ministry of Information and Broadcasting of the Government of India and aided by the Central Government of India. It is situated on the premises of the erstwhile Prabhat Film Company in Pune.

question_text: Georgia, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan became the members of UNO in
explanation: Georgia, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan became the members of UNO in 1992.

explanation: Guru Gobind Singh (1666 - 1708). The 10th Guru of the Sikhs who founded the Khalsa the inner council of the Sikhs in 1699. He is said to be the author of Dasam Granth.

question_text: Hermann Scheer (Germany) received right Livelihood Award in 1999 for
option_A: his long standing efforts to end the impunity of dictators
option_B: his indefatigable work for the promotion of solar energy worldwide
option_C: showing that organic agriculture is a key to both environmental sustainability and food security
answer: his indefatigable work for the promotion of solar energy worldwide
explanation: Hermann Scheer (Germany) received right Livelihood Award in 1999 for his indefatigable work for the promotion of solar energy worldwide. Hermann Scheer was a Social Democrat member of the German Bundestag, President of Eurosolar and General Chairman of the World Council for Renewable Energy.

question_text: Germany signed the Armistice Treaty on ____ and World War I ended
explanation: Germany signed the Armistice Treaty on November 11, 1918 and World War I ended.

question_text: During World War II, when did Germany attack France?
explanation: During World War II, 1940 Germany attack France. The Battle of France, also known as the Fall of France, was the German invasion of France and the Low Countries during the Second World War. On 3 September 1939 France had declared war on Germany, following the invasion of its ally Poland.

question_text: Frederick Sanger is a twice recipient of the Nobel Prize for
explanation: Frederick SangerBorn August 13, 1918, Rendcombe, Gloucestershire, England.English biochemist who was twice the recipient of the Nobel Prize for Chemistry. He was awarded the prize in 1958 for his determination of the structure of the insulin molecule. He shared the prize (with Paul Berg and Walter Gilbert) in 1980 for his determination of base sequences in nucleic acids. Sanger was only the fourth two-time recipient of the Nobel Prize.

question_text: The ozone layer restricts
explanation: The ozone layer restricts ultraviolet radiation. The Ozone layer which is present in the Earth's atmosphere protects it by restricting from UV or Ultraviolet radiation, the dangerous rays contained by Sun.

question_text: Eugenics is the study of
option_D: altering human beings by changing their genetic components
answer: altering human beings by changing their genetic components
explanation: Eugenics is the study of or belief in the possibility of improving the qualities of the human species or a human population, especially by such means as discouraging reproduction by persons having genetic defects or presumed to have inheritable undesirable traits (negative eugenics) or encouraging reproduction by persons presumed to have inheritable desirable traits (positive eugenics)

question_text: Euclid was
option_C: Contributor to the use of deductive principles of logic as the basis of geometry
explanation: Euclid was Greek mathematician, propounded the geometrical theorems and contributor to the use of deductive principles of logic as the basis of geometry.

question_text: Ecology deals with
option_C: Relation between organisms and their environment
answer: Relation between organisms and their environment
explanation: Ecology deals with relation between organisms and their environment. Ecology is the study of the interaction of organisms in an area with their environment. This interaction constitutes an overall adaptation of the organisms to their environment which also includes the continuity of species. However, the availability of organisms in an area is dependent on the type of environment.

question_text: Filaria is caused by
explanation: Filaria is caused by Mosquito. Filariasis is a parasitic disease caused by an infection with roundworms of the Filarioidea type. These are spread by blood-feeding diptera such as black flies and mosquitoes.

explanation: Goa Shipyard Limited (GSL) was established in 1957. It is a leading ISO 9001-2015 certified shipyard on the West Coast of India, functioning under the administrative control of Ministry of Defence, Govt. of India.

explanation: DRDL stands for Defence Research and Development Laboratary, under the Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) - with thrust on design, development and flight evaluation of various types of Missile Systems for the Indian armed forces.

question_text: Who was the first Indian Chief of Army Staff of the Indian Army ?
explanation: Gen. Maharaja Rajendra Singhji was the first Indian Chief of Army Staff of the Indian Army. General Maharaj Shri Rajendrasinhji Jadeja, DSO (15 June 1899 – 1 January 1964), also known as K.S. Rajendrasinhji, was the first Chief of Army Staff of the Indian army, and the second Indian, after Field Marshal K. M.

question_text: FRS stands for
explanation: FRS stands for Fellow of Royal Society. Fellowship of the Royal Society (FRS, ForMemRS and HonFRS) is an award granted to individuals that the Royal Society of London judges to have made a 'substantial contribution to the improvement of natural knowledge, including mathematics, engineering science, and medical science'.

question_text: Escape velocity of a rocket fired from the earth towards the moon is a velocity to get rid of the

explanation: Escape velocity of a rocket fired from the earth towards the moon is a velocity to get rid of the Earth's gravitational pull.

explanation: Coral reefs in India can be found in Rameshwaram. Coral reefs on the Tamil Nadu coast are located in Palk Bay near Rameswaram and in the Gulf of Mannar.

explanation: For safety, the fuse wire used in the mains for household supply of electricity must be made of metal having low melting point.

option_C: Both option A and B are correct
explanation: Golden Temple, Amritsar is India's largest Gurdwara. The Golden Temple Amritsar India (Sri Harimandir Sahib Amritsar) is not only a central religious place of the Sikhs, but also a symbol of human brotherhood and equality. Everybody, irrespective of cast, creed or race can seek spiritual solace and religious fulfilment without any hindrance. It also represents the distinct identity, glory and heritage of the Sikhs.

question_text: During World War I Germany was defeated in the Battle of Verdun on the western front and Romania declared war on the eastern front in the year
explanation: During World War I Germany was defeated in the Battle of Verdun on the western front and Romania declared war on the eastern front in the year 1916 AD. Germany signed an armistice (an agreement for peace and no more fighting) that had been prepared by Britain and France. At the start of 1918, Germany was in a strong position and expected to win the war.

explanation: Heavy Water Project (Talcher) and Fertilizer plant (Paradeep) are famous industries of Orissa.

question_text: Hamid Karzai was chosen president of Afghanistan in
explanation: Hamid Karzai was chosen president of Afghanistan in 2002. The Karzai administration was the government of Afghanistan under President Hamid Karzai, who became the head of state of Afghanistan in December 2001 after the Taliban government was overthrown. Karzai was appointed at the 2002 Loya Jirga as the Interim President of the Afghan Transitional Administration.

question_text: Durand Cup is associated with the game of
explanation: Durand Cup is associated with the game of Football. The Tournament is the oldest football tournament in Asia and third oldest in the world.

question_text: Headquarters of UNO are situated at
explanation: The headquarters of the United Nations is a distinctive complex in New York City (USA). The United Nations has three additional, subsidiary, regional headquarters or headquarter districts. These are located in Geneva (Switzerland), Vienna (Austria), and Nairobi (Kenya).

question_text: First International Peace Congress was held in London in
explanation: First International Peace Congress was held in London in 1843 AD. The first International Congress was held in London at the suggestion of Joseph Sturge and on the initiative of the American Peace Society in 1843. The host was the London Peace Society. 294 British, 37 American and six Continental delegates attended.

question_text: For seeing objects at the surface of water from a submarine under water, the instrument used is
explanation: For seeing objects at the surface of water from a submarine under water, the instrument used is periscope. It can be through or around the object that made it visible. In addition to this, it avoids any sort of direct sight line from the point of observation to the object being observed.

question_text: Dr. Zakir Hussain was
option_C: the first Muslim president of India
option_D: first president of Indian National Congress
answer: the first Muslim president of India
explanation: Dr. Zakir Hussain was the first Muslim president of India. He was the co-founder of Jamia Millia Islamia University. Born on February 8, 1897, in Hyderabad, he was the country's first Muslim president, from May 13, 1967, until his death on May 3, 1969.

question_text: G-15 is an economic grouping of
explanation: G-15 is an economic grouping of Third World Nations. The countries listed in G-15 group are Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Iran, Jamaica, Kenya, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri Lanka, Venezuela, and Zimbabwe.

question_text: Fathometer is used to measure
explanation: Fathometer is used to measure Ocean depth. Fathometer is a depth finder that uses sound waves to determine the depth of water. The Richter Scale is used to measure the intensity of Earthquakes.

question_text: For galvanizing iron which of the following metals is used?
explanation: Zinc is used for galvanizing iron. Galvanization (or galvanizing as it is most commonly called in that industry) is the process of applying a protective zinc coating to steel or iron, to prevent rusting.

question_text: Economic goods are
option_A: Commodities that is available according to their demand
option_B: Commodities that is available more as compared to demand
option_C: all commodities that are limited in quantity as compared to their demand
answer: all commodities that are limited in quantity as compared to their demand
explanation: Economic goods are all commodities that are limited in quantity as compared to their demand. An economic good is a good or service that has a benefit (utility) to society. Also, economic goods have a degree of scarcity and therefore an opportunity cost.

question_text: For purifying drinking water alum is used
explanation: For purifying drinking water alum is used for coagulation of mud particles. Aluminium Sulfate, Shortly known as Alum, when added to raw water reacts with the bicarbonate alkalinities present in water and forms a gelatinous precipitate. The water over this sediment is almost clean other than some fine particles dissolved in it.

question_text: Hockey was introduced in the Asian Games in
explanation: Hockey was introduced in the Asian Games in 1958 in Tokyo. Field hockey was contested for men only at the 1958 Asian Games in Tokyo, Japan between 25 May and 30 May 1958 with five teams participating in a round robin competition.

question_text: ESCAP stands for
option_A: European Society Council for Africa and Pacific
option_B: Economic and Social Commission for Asia and Pacific
option_C: Economic and Social Commission for Africa and Pacific
answer: Economic and Social Commission for Asia and Pacific
explanation: ESCAP stands for Economic and Social Commission for Asia and Pacific. The Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) serves as the United Nations' regional hub promoting cooperation among countries to achieve inclusive and sustainable development.

question_text: Firdausi was
explanation: Firdausi was a poet and well known for his epic 'Shahnama'. Firdausi was a well known poet of Mahmud of Ghazni and wrote a book ,Shahnama, which is about the history of Persia.

question_text: Himalayan Mountaineering Institute is at
explanation: Himalayan Mountaineering Institute is at Darjeeling. It is recognized as one of the best mountaineering institutes in the world.

question_text: Gabriel Daniel Fahrenheit was
explanation: Gabriel Daniel Fahrenheit was a German Physicist, devised temperature scale and developed the mercury thermometer in 1714. He invented the alcohol thermometer (1709), the first mercury thermometer (1714) and devised the Fahrenheit temperature scale. He also showed the boiling points of liquids vary with changes in pressure and that water can remain liquid below its freezing point.

question_text: During the first crusade, crusaders reached Jerusalem and captured it in
explanation: During the first crusade, crusaders reached Jerusalem and captured it in 1099 AD. They arrived at Jerusalem in June 1099 and took the city by assault on 7 July 1099, massacring the defenders. A brief attempt by the Saracens to recapture Jerusalem was repulsed at the Battle of Ascalon.

question_text: Dr. Linus Carl Pauling is the only person to have won two Nobel prizes individually for
explanation: Dr. Linus Carl Pauling is the only person to have won two Nobel prizes individually for Chemistry in 1954, Peace Prize in 1962. He is one of four individuals to have won more than one Nobel Prize (the others being Marie Curie, John Bardeen and Frederick Sanger).

question_text: Free market is
option_A: a condition in the international market where nations do not impose customs duty or other taxes on import of goods
option_B: market where the price of a commodity is determined by free play of the forces of supply and demand
option_C: ports that are exempted from payment of customs duty on articles of commerce, primarily to encourage tourism
answer: market where the price of a commodity is determined by free play of the forces of supply and demand
explanation: Free market is market where the price of a commodity is determined by free play of the forces of supply and demand. The free market is an economic system based on supply and demand with little or no government control. It is a summary description of all voluntary exchanges that take place in a given economic environment.

question_text: East Timor, which became the 191st member of the UN, is in the continent of
explanation: East Timor, which became the 191st member of the UN, is in the continent of Asia. East Timor became the first new sovereign state of the 21st century on 20 May 2002 and joined the United Nations and the Community of Portuguese Language Countries.

question_text: Free surface of a liquid behaves like a sheet and tends to contract to the smallest possible area due to the
explanation: Free surface of a liquid behaves like a sheet and tends to contract to the smallest possible area due to the force of cohesion. The force of cohesion is defined as the force of attraction between molecules of the same substance.

explanation: GNLF stands for Gorkha National Liberation Front. Gorkha National Liberation Front (GNLF) is a political party in the Darjeeling District of West Bengal, India.

explanation: Excessive secretion from the pituitary gland in the children results in increased height. In children and adolescents, excessive levels of growth hormone can result in a condition called gigantism. Children with this condition may have unusually long arms and legs and may grow to heights of 7 to 8 feet or more.

question_text: In which year of First World War Germany declared war on Russia and France?
explanation: August 3, 1914 - Germany declares war on France, and invades neutral Belgium.

question_text: India's first atomic reactor was
explanation: India's first atomic reactor was Apsara. Apsara is the oldest of India's research reactors. The reactor was designed by the Bhabha Atomic Research Center (BARC) and built with assistance from the United Kingdom (which also provided the initial fuel supply consisting of 80 percent enriched uranium). Apsara first went critical on 4 August 1956.

question_text: In which year, terrorists crash two planes into New York's World Trade Centre on September 11 in a sequence of destruction?
explanation: In year 2001, terrorists crash two planes into New York's World Trade Centre on September 11 in a sequence of destruction. It was the deadliest terrorist attack on U.S. soil; nearly 3,000 people were killed.

question_text: India's first ocean wave's energy project was launched in
explanation: India's first ocean wave's energy project was launched in 1991.

explanation: India's tallest stone statue of the Jain sage Gomateswara is at Sravanabelagola, Karnataka. Shravanabelagola (Śravaṇa Beḷagoḷa) is a town located near Channarayapatna of Hassan district in the Indian state of Karnataka.

question_text: In 1945, fifty nations met to phrase the basic charter for a world organization which would "save succeeding generations from the scourge of war". This conference took place at
explanation: In 1945, fifty nations met to phrase the basic charter for a world organization which would "save succeeding generations from the scourge of war". This conference took place at San Francisco.

question_text: In a normal human body, the total number of red blood cells is
explanation: In a normal human body, the total number of red blood cells is 30 trillion. Women have roughly 4 to 5 million red blood cells per microliter of blood, whereas men have about 5 to 6 million per microliter of blood. Red blood cells comprise approximately 70% of total human body cell number.

question_text: INS Venduruthy is located at
explanation: INS Venduruthy is an Indian Navy base located on Willingdon Island in Kochi, Kerala. It serves as the Headquarters of the Southern Naval Command.

question_text: In which season do we need more fat?
explanation: In Winter season we need more fat. Researchers suggest that we have a natural tendency to overeat in the winter because, historically, food was more scarce.

question_text: How much districts are there in Punjab?
explanation: There are 22 districts in Punjab. The districts listed are: Amritsar, Bathinda, Faridkot, Firozpur, Fatehgarh Sahib, Kapurthala, Gurdaspur, Hoshiarpur, Jalandhar, Ludhiana, Mansa, Moga, Muktsar, Nawanshahr, Patiala, Rupnagar, Sangrur, and Tarn Taran.

question_text: India participated in Olympics Hockey in
explanation: India participated in Olympics Hockey in 1928. The 1928 Olympics in Amsterdam, when India won the gold, was the country's first step towards ascending the hockey throne.

question_text: If force is expressed in Newton and the distance in metre, then the work done is expressed in
explanation: If force is expressed in Newton and the distance in metre, then the work done is expressed in Joule. Work done is expressed in force divided by distance. SI unit is joule.

question_text: How many teeth does a normal adult dog have?
explanation: Adult dogs have 42 permanent teeth compared to a measly 32 average human teeth (not counting any wisdom teeth. Those are "bonus"). Puppies possess 28 baby teeth while human babies will have 20 deciduous or “baby” teeth.

question_text: How many red blood cells does the bone marrow produce every second?
explanation: 10 million red blood cells the bone marrow produce every second. The formation of a red blood cell from hemocytoblast takes about 2 days. The body makes about two million red blood cells every second.

question_text: How many times has Brazil won the World Cup Football Championship?
explanation: Brazil have won five times, and they are the only team to have played in every tournament. The other World Cup winners are Germany and Italy, with four titles each; Argentina, France and inaugural winner Uruguay, with two titles each; and England and Spain with one title each.

question_text: If speed of rotation of the earth increases, weight of the body
explanation: If speed of rotation of the earth increases, weight of the body decreases. This is because you see a moving body on the rotating earth's surface itself is in the reference frame. So when the earth rotates, the centripetal force acts towards the centre of rotation.

question_text: In August, 1996 at Kolar(near Bangalore), India made successful test flights of Unmanned Air Vehicle (UAV) named
explanation: In August, 1996 at Kolar(near Bangalore), India made successful test flights of Unmanned Air Vehicle (UAV) named Nishant. The DRDO Nishant was an Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) developed by India's ADE (Aeronautical Development Establishment), a branch of DRDO (Defence Research and Development Organisation) for the Indian Armed Forces.

question_text: IDA stands for
explanation: IDA stands for International Development Agency. The International Development Association (IDA) is the part of the World Bank that helps the world’s poorest countries. It was established in 1960 to complement the existing International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) by lending to developing countries which suffer from the lowest gross national income, from troubled creditworthiness, or from the lowest per capita income.

question_text: Indira Gandhi was assassinated in
explanation: Indira Gandhi was assassinated in 1984. On 31 October 1984, Indira Gandhi, Prime Minister of India, was killed by her Sikh bodyguards. The assassination sparked four days of riots that left more than 8,000 Indian Sikhs dead in revenge attacks.

question_text: India's first nuclear blast at Pokhran in Rajasthan took place in
explanation: India's first nuclear blast at Pokhran in Rajasthan took place in 1974. The bomb was detonated on the army base Pokhran Test Range (PTR), in Rajasthan, by the Indian Army under the supervision of several key Indian generals.

question_text: How many players are there on each side in the game of Basketball?
explanation: Basketball is a team sport where two teams, usually consisting of five players on each team, play against each other on a rectangular court.

question_text: In a normal human being, how much time does food take to reach the end of the intestine for complete absorption?
explanation: In a normal human being, food take about 12 hours to reach the end of the intestine for complete absorption. Food then enters your large intestine (colon) for further digestion, absorption of water and, finally, elimination of undigested food.

question_text: In certain diseases antibiotics are administered. The object is
option_D: stimulate production of white blood cells for fighting the disease
explanation: In certain diseases antibiotics are administered. The object is inhibit the growth of bacteria. An antimicrobial is a substance that kills or inhibits the growth of microorganisms such as bacteria, fungi, or protozoans. Antimicrobial drugs either kill microbes (microbiocidal) or prevent the growth of microbes (microbiostatic).

question_text: In cricket, the two sets of wickets are
explanation: In cricket, the two sets of wickets are 22 yards apart.

question_text: India's first indigenous helicopter was successfully flown in Bangalore on
explanation: India's first indigenous helicopter was successfully flown in Bangalore on August 30, 1992. The country's first indigenous chopper, Advanced Light Helicopter (ALH -Dhruv), designed, developed, produced and maintained by Hindustan Aeronautics Ltd to meet the requirement of military and civil operators, today achieved a new milestone of clocking one lakh cumulative flying hours.

question_text: In which of the followings places was the last Winter Olympics Games held?
explanation: In Vancouver, the last Winter Olympics Games held. The city of Vancouver was elected host city of the XXI Olympic Winter Games in 2010 at the 115th IOC Session in Prague on 2 July 2003.

question_text: Hundred year war was fought between
explanation: Hundred year war was fought between France and England during the late Middle Ages. It lasted 116 years from 1337 to 1453. The war started because Charles IV of France died in 1328 without an immediate male heir (i.e., a son or younger brother).

question_text: In which of the following pairs, the two substances forming the pair are chemically most dissimilar?
explanation: In Butter and paraffin wax, the two substances forming the pair are chemically most dissimilar. Butter is an unsaturated compound or an olefin in contrast to wax which is a saturated compound. So butter will show more reactivity for reactants. As such, they show different chemical nature.

question_text: India's Integrated Missiles Development Programme was started in ____ under the chairmanship of Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam.
explanation: India's Integrated Missiles Development Programme was started in 1982-83 under the chairmanship of Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam. On 8 January 2008, the DRDO formally announced the successful completion of the IGMDP.

question_text: INS Agrani (Petty Officers' School) is situated at
explanation: INS Agrani (Petty Officers' School) is situated at Coimbatore. Indian Naval Station Agrani is a leadership training establishment of the Indian Navy, it comes under the Eastern Naval Command and conducts courses for middle level sailors. This station was commissioned in 1965.

question_text: Hybridization is
option_B: a process of tilling the land
option_D: downward movement of water through soil
explanation: Hybridization is cross-fertilization between two varieties. Hybridization refers to the natural or deliberate pollination between two plants. It occurs all the time in the wild as many plants are cross-pollinated and when the pollen from one plant lands on the stigma of another plant, and if fertilization is successful in producing seed, then hybridization has occurred.

question_text: In which world cup cricket final, Australia beat England?
explanation: In 1987, Kolkata - India world cup cricket final, Australia beat England. The final of the Reliance World Cup was played in Eden Gardens, Calcutta on Sunday 8 November 1987. The match was won by Australia who defeated England by 7 runs to lift their first ever World Cup trophy. This was the first Cricket World Cup final to be played outside England.

question_text: India is the ____ grower of pulses.
explanation: India is the largest grower of pulses. Madhya Pradesh is India's largest pulse producing state, which accounts for 23% of total pulse production in the country. Madhya Pradesh is followed by Uttar Pradesh (18%), Maharashtra (14%), Rajasthan (11%) and Andhra Pradesh (9%).

question_text: In cricket, a run taken when the ball passes the batsman without touching his bat or body is called
explanation: In cricket, a run taken when the ball passes the batsman without touching his bat or body is called bye. A bye is a run scored by the batting team when the ball has not been hit by the batsman and the ball has not hit the batsman's body.

question_text: How many non-permanent Security Council (UNO) members are from Afro-Asian countries?
explanation: 5 non-permanent Security Council (UNO) members are from Afro-Asian countries.

question_text: Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research, established in 1971, is located at
explanation: Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research, established in 1971, is located at Kalpakkam, Chennai. Indira Gandhi Centre for Atomic Research (IGCAR) is one of India's premier nuclear research centres. It is the second largest establishment of the Department of Atomic Energy (DAE), next to Bhabha Atomic Research Centre (BARC), located at Kalpakkam, 80 km south of Chennai, India. It was established in 1971 as an exclusive centre dedicated to the pursuit of fast reactor science and technology, due to the vision of Dr. Vikram Sarabhai.

question_text: In which year did Sir Edmund Hillary reach the summit of Mount Everest?
explanation: Edmund Percival Hillary, born in Auckland New Zealand in the year 1919, was the first to reach the summit of Mount Everest together with Sherpa Tenzing Norgay on May 29, 1953.A man with a heart !! Died on the 11 January 2008, a sad loss to New Zealand.

question_text: India's first fast breeder neutron reactor was
explanation: India's first fast breeder neutron reactor was Kamini. KAMINI (Kalpakkam Mini reactor) is a research reactor at Indira Gandhi Center for Atomic Research in Kalpakkam, India. It achieved criticality on October 29, 1996.

question_text: India's first atomic power station was set up at
explanation: India's first atomic power station was set up at Tarapur (Maharashtra), is the oldest nuclear power plant in India. The power station comprises two 120MW boiling water reactor (BWR) units commissioned in October 1969 and two pressurised heavy water reactor (PHWR) units commissioned between 2005 and 2006.

question_text: How many Ergs are there in 1 joule?
explanation: 1 Joule = 1 Newton × 1 m displacement = 105 dyne × 100 cm displacement = 107 ergs.1 Joule = 107 ergs.

question_text: In 1943, Franklin D. Roosevelt, Winston Churchill and Joseph Stalin met at Teheran primarily
option_A: to work out a common line of action against Japan
option_B: for creating an effective instrument for maintaining international peace
option_C: to discuss the strategy to be adopted by the Allies to invade Germany
option_D: to consider a common plan of action by the Allies forces against the axis powers
answer: for creating an effective instrument for maintaining international peace
explanation: In 1943, Franklin D. Roosevelt, Winston Churchill and Joseph Stalin met at Teheran primarily for creating an effective instrument for maintaining international peace.

question_text: Innocent III, who became pope in 1198 led
explanation: Innocent III, who became pope in 1198 led the fourth crusade. The Fourth Crusade (1202-1204 CE) was called by Pope Innocent III (r. 1198-1216 CE) to retake Jerusalem from its current Muslim overlords.

question_text: In which year a resolution 'Uniting for Peace' was adopted by UN General Assembly?
explanation: In 1950 a resolution 'Uniting for Peace' was adopted by UN General Assembly. The Uniting for Peace resolution was initiated by the United States, and submitted by the "Joint Seven-Powers" in October 1950, as a means of circumventing further Soviet vetoes during the course of the Korean War (25 June 1950 – 27 July 1953). It was adopted by 52 votes to 5, with 2 abstentions.

question_text: In which of the following organs of human body does maximum absorption of food take place?
explanation: In Small intestine of human body does maximum absorption of food take place. The small intestine or small bowel is an organ in the gastrointestinal tract where most of the end absorption of nutrients and minerals from food takes place.

question_text: Human Rights Day is on
explanation: Human Rights Day is on 10 December. This day is celebrated internationally to honor 10th Dec 1948, when the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights at Palais de Challoit, Paris after the experience of the Second World War.

question_text: In the 2002 World Cup Hockey Finals, Germany beat ____
explanation: In the 2002 World Cup Hockey Finals, Germany beat Australia. The 2002 Men's Hockey World Cup was the 10th edition of the Hockey World Cup, a men's field hockey tournament. It was held from 24 February to 9 March 2002 in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. Germany won their first title after defeating Australia 2–1 in the final.

question_text: How much of blood does the normal human heart on each of its contraction pump into the arteries?
explanation: The normal human heart on each of its contraction pumps 60 cm3 of blood into the arteries.

question_text: Hygrometer is used to measure
explanation: Hygrometer is used to measure relative humidity. Humidity is the measure of the amount of moisture in the air. A psychrometer is an example of a hygrometer.

question_text: India became a member of the United Nations in
explanation: India became a member of the United Nations in 1945. India is a founding member of the United Nations. On June 26, 1945, India was among 50 countries to sign the UN charter. India joined the United Nations after ratifying the UN Charter on October 30, 1945.

question_text: India has
explanation: India has largest turmeric production, largest tea production and largest ginger production.

question_text: India's first indigenously built submarine was
explanation: INS Shalki (S46) is a Shishumar-class diesel-electric submarine of the Indian Navy. The submarine was the first ever submarine to be built in India. It was launched in 1987 by the late Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.

question_text: How many medals came into the account of India during the 2002 Commonwealth Games at Manchester?
explanation: 69 medals came into the account of India during the 2002 Commonwealth Games at Manchester. India won unprecedented 69 medals including 30 gold, 22 silver and 17 bronze and were fourth in the medal tally.

question_text: If the plane of the earth's equator were not inclined to the plane of the earth's orbit
option_D: there would be no change of seasons
answer: there would be no change of seasons
explanation: If the plane of the earth's equator were not inclined to the plane of the earth's orbit there would be no change of seasons. When tilted, the hemisphere closer to the sun would experience summer, while the hemisphere that is relatively farther away would experience winter. If the earth were not tilted, the whole planet would be relatively equidistant from the sun, and hence, no seasons.

question_text: India played its first cricket Test Match in
explanation: India played its first cricket Test Match in 1932. India was invited to The Imperial Cricket Council in 1926, and made their debut as a Test playing nation in England in 1932, led by CK Nayudu, who was considered as the best Indian batsman at the time. The one-off Test match between the two sides was played at Lord's in London.

question_text: India has been represented as a non-permanent member of the Security Council (UNO) during
explanation: India has been represented as a non-permanent member of the Security Council (UNO) during 1972-73, 1984-85 and 1991-92.

question_text: How many Lok Sabha seats does Goa have?
explanation: Goa have two Lok Sabha seats. South Goa Lok Sabha constituency (formerly, Mormugao Lok Sabha constituency) is one of two Lok Sabha (parliamentary) constituencies in Goa in western India along with North Goa.

question_text: In Air Force, Air Commodore has one rank higher than
explanation: In Air Force, Air Commodore has one rank higher than Group Captain. Air commodore is a one-star rank and the most junior air officer rank, being immediately senior to group captain and immediately subordinate to air vice-marshal. It has a NATO ranking code of OF-6 and is equivalent to a commodore in the Royal Navy or a brigadier in the British Army or the Royal Marines.

question_text: How much districts are there in Tamil Nadu?
explanation: There are 33 districts in Tamil Nadu.

question_text: How much districts are there in Meghalaya?
explanation: Meghalaya currently has 11 districts.

question_text: How many Dynes are there in 1 gram weight?
explanation: There are 981 dynes in one gram weight. Dyne is a CGS unit.

question_text: In big cities like Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Chennai police is headed by a
explanation: In big cities like Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Chennai police is headed by a Commissioner of Police. Police commissioners serve their communities by overseeing police departments, either as sworn officers or as civilians selected to sit on a board of police commissioners.

question_text: Indian Institute of Petroleum is located at
explanation: Indian Institute of Petroleum is located at Dehradun. Indian Institute of Petroleum is situated in Dehradun in Uttarakhand state of India. It is established in 1960.

question_text: In which of the following team events India got a Gold Medal at the 2002 Asian Games?
explanation: In Kabaddi India got a Gold Medal at the 2002 Asian Games. Jagdish Kumble is an Indian professional kabaddi player and coach. He was member of the India national kabaddi team that won Asian games gold medals in 2002 which was held at Busan.

question_text: In which year during World War I, USA declared war on Germany, Britain defeated Turkey and captured Baghdad and Jerusalem?
explanation: In 1917 during World War I, USA declared war on Germany, Britain defeated Turkey and captured Baghdad and Jerusalem.

question_text: In 1947, Algeria became politically unified with France but the 80 percent population revolted against French domination
explanation: In 1947, Algeria became politically unified with France but the 80 percent population revolted against French domination Muslim.

question_text: In UNO, the new members are admitted to the General Assembly on the recommendation of ____ and ____ the members of the General Assembly should vote in favour.
explanation: In UNO, the new members are admitted to the General Assembly on the recommendation of Security Council and two-third of the members of the General Assembly should vote in favour.

question_text: Squadron leader Rakesh Sharma was India's first man to go into space. He was ____ cosmonaut to be in space in the world.
explanation: Squadron leader Rakesh Sharma was India's first man to go into space. He was 139th cosmonaut to be in space in the world. Sharma progressed through numerous levels and in 1984, he was appointed as a squadron leader and pilot in the Indian Air Force. He was selected on 20 September 1982 to become a cosmonaut and go into space as part of a joint program between the Indian Air Force and the Soviet Interkosmos space program.

question_text: Philology is the
explanation: Philology is the science of languages. Philology, traditionally, the study of the history of language, including the historical study of literary texts.

question_text: The 2006 World Cup Football Tournament held in
explanation: The 2006 World Cup Football Tournament held in Germany. It was held from 9 June to 9 July 2006 in Germany, which won the right to host the event in July 2000.

question_text: Satellite launching station is located at
explanation: Satellite launching station is located at Sriharikotta (Andhra Pradesh). Satish Dhawan Space Centre (SDSC) or Sriharikota Range (SHAR) is a rocket launch centre operated by the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO). It is located in Sriharikota in Andhra Pradesh. Sriharikota Range was renamed in 2002 after ISRO's former chairman Satish Dhawan.

question_text: The 'Black flag' signifies
explanation: The 'Black flag' signifies protest.

question_text: Republican party is
option_A: One of the important parties in USA
option_B: the political parties which has no definite principles
option_C: the political party which changes with the change in the times and circumstances in the country
explanation: Republican party is One of the important parties in USA, the political parties which has no definite principles and is the political party which changes with the change in the times and circumstances in the country.

question_text: Study of life in outer space is known as
explanation: Study of life in outer space is known as exobiology. This branch of science deals with nature of possible life forms on other planets. It is understanding evolution, distribution, origin, and future of life beyond our Earth. There are a lot of ongoing researches going on about the potential of other life forms in the outer space.

question_text: School of Aviation Medicine (Air Force) is located at
explanation: School of Aviation Medicine (Air Force) is located at Bangalore.

question_text: Recession is
option_A: slowing down of economic activity over a limited period
option_B: period that results from accumulation of unsold goods, owing to fall in demand
option_C: period during which unemployment may rise and demand and output may fall, leading to slump in trade
explanation: Recession is slowing down of economic activity over a limited period, period that results from accumulation of unsold goods, owing to fall in demand and period during which unemployment may rise and demand and output may fall, leading to slump in trade.

question_text: Sir Thomas Fearnley Cup is awarded to
option_A: amateur athlete, not necessarily an Olympian
option_B: National Olympic Committee for outstanding work
option_C: a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements
answer: a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements
explanation: Sir Thomas Fearnley Cup is awarded to a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements. Fearnley became Honorary Member of the IOC 1951. In 1950, he founded the Fearnley Cup to honor an amateur sport club or a local amateur sport association based upon meritorious achievement in the service of the Olympic Movement. He originated the Fearnley Olympic Award in connection with the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo. The award is given for outstanding achievements by a Norwegian Olympic participant.

question_text: Pythagoras was first to ____ the universal validity of geometrical theorem.
explanation: Pythagoras was first to prove the universal validity of geometrical theorem. He is known best for the proof of the important Pythagorean theorem, which is about right angle triangles.

question_text: Soil acidity is generally corrected by
explanation: Soil acidity is generally corrected by liming. Soil acidity can be corrected easily by liming the soil, or adding basic materials to neutralize the acid present. The most commonly used liming material is agricultural limestone, the most economical and relatively easy to manage source. The limestone is not very water-soluble, making it easy to handle.

question_text: Oscar Awards were instituted in
explanation: Oscar Awards were instituted in 1929. The 1st Academy Awards ceremony, presented by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), honored the best films of 1927 and 1928 and took place on May 16, 1929, at a private dinner held at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel in Los Angeles, California.

question_text: Small amounts of iodine are necessary in our diet to
option_D: compensate for underactive the thyroid gland
answer: compensate for underactive the thyroid gland
explanation: Small amounts of iodine are necessary in our diet to compensate for underactive the thyroid gland. When blood levels of TSH rise, the thyroid gland uses iodine to make thyroid hormones. However, when your body is low in iodine, it can't make enough of them.

question_text: Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Service is an International Airline of
explanation: Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Service is an International Airline of Australia. Qantas, in full Qantas Airways Limited, Australian airline, the oldest in the English-speaking world, founded in 1920 as Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Services Ltd. (from which the name Qantas was derived).

question_text: Shaurya Chakra made up of bronze is awarded for
option_A: gallantry in the presence of enemy
option_B: gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy
option_C: most conspicuous bravery for some act of self sacrifice
answer: gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy
explanation: Shaurya Chakra made up of bronze is awarded for gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy. The Shaurya Chakra is an Indian military decoration awarded for valour, courageous action or self-sacrifice while not engaged in direct action with the enemy. It may be awarded to civilians as well as military personnel, sometimes posthumously.

question_text: Sushri Lata Dinanath Mangeshkar received Bharath Ratna in
explanation: Sushri Lata Dinanath Mangeshkar received Bharath Ratna in 2001. She is one of the best-known and most respected playback singers in India. She has recorded songs in over a thousand Hindi films and has sung songs in over thirty-six regional Indian languages and foreign languages, though primarily in Marathi, Hindi, and Bengali.

question_text: Taoism is followed in
option_C: China, Taiwan, Nauru, Brunei, Singapore and Vietnam
answer: China, Taiwan, Nauru, Brunei, Singapore and Vietnam
explanation: Taoism is a Chinese philosophy attributed to Lao Tzu which contributed to the folk religion of the people primarily in the rural areas of China and became the official religion of the country under the Tang Dynasty. Taoism is therefore both a philosophy and a religion. Taoism is also known as Daoism.

question_text: The 2005 Wimbledon Women's Singles champion defeated which of the following to win the title?
explanation: The 2005 Wimbledon Women's Singles champion defeated Lindsay Davenport to win the title. It was the longest Wimbledon women's final match in history, lasting two hours and 45 minutes.

question_text: Sheikh Mujibur Rahman is a well known freedom fighter of
explanation: Sheikh Mujibur Rahman is a well known freedom fighter of Bangladesh. He is often called the father of Bengali nation. He served as the first President of Bangladesh and later as the Prime Minister of Bangladesh from 17 April 1971 until his assassination on 15 August 1975. He is considered to be the driving force behind the independence of Bangladesh. He is popularly dubbed with the title of "Bangabandhu" (Bôngobondhu "Friend of Bengal") by the people of Bangladesh. He became a leading figure in and eventually the leader of the Awami League, founded in 1949 as an East Pakistan-based political party in Pakistan.

question_text: Shares with a fixed rate of dividend that entitle their holders to priority payment over those who hold ordinary shares of a company are called
explanation: Shares with a fixed rate of dividend that entitle their holders to priority payment over those who hold ordinary shares of a company are called preference shares. Preference shares are the shares which promise the holder a fixed dividend, whose payment takes priority over that of ordinary share dividends.

question_text: Shankracharya was the founder of
explanation: Shankracharya was the founder of Advaitic philosophy. He was an early 8th century Indian philosopher and theologian who consolidated the doctrine of Advaita Vedanta. He is credited with unifying and establishing the main currents of thought in Hinduism.

question_text: Sculpture flourished during
explanation: Sculpture flourished during Indus valley civilization. People from this civilisation created sculpture, seals, pottery, and jewellery from materials, such as terracotta, metal, and stone.

question_text: Penicillin is widely used as
explanation: Penicillin is widely used as an antibiotic. Penicillins are a group of antibacterial drugs that attack a wide range of bacteria. They were the first drugs of this type that doctors used. The discovery and manufacture of penicillins have changed the face of medicine, as these drugs have saved millions of lives.

question_text: Socrates was the wisest man of the ancient world and developed the method of enquiry and instruction, belonged to
explanation: Socrates was the wisest man of the ancient world and developed the method of enquiry and instruction, belonged to Athens. Socrates was a classical Greek philosopher credited as one of the founders of Western philosophy, and as being the first moral philosopher of the Western ethical tradition of thought.

question_text: Richter scale is used for measuring
explanation: Richter scale is used for measuring intensity of earthquakes. The Richter scale measures the maximum amplitude of seismic waves as they reach seismographs. This scale is expressed with a logarithmic scale. Thus, an earthquake measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale would be 10 times larger than an earthquake that measures 6.0.

question_text: Prince Charles and Princess Diana of Britain announce their separation in
explanation: Prince Charles and Princess Diana of Britain announce their separation in 1996. In July 1996, the couple agreed on the terms of their divorce.

question_text: Paleontology is a branch of science that deals with the
option_D: forms of life as revealed by fossils of animals or plants
answer: forms of life as revealed by fossils of animals or plants
explanation: Paleontology is a branch of science that deals with the forms of life as revealed by fossils of animals or plants. Paleontology is the study of the history of life on Earth as based on fossils. Fossils are the remains of plants, animals, fungi, bacteria, and single-celled living things that have been replaced by rock material or impressions of organisms preserved in rock.

question_text: Sir Humphry Davy was a British chemist who
option_A: invented the safety lamp for miners
option_B: discovered the anesthetic properties of nitrous oxide
explanation: Sir Humphry Davy was a British chemist who invented the safety lamp for miners and discovered the anesthetic properties of nitrous oxide. He was an English chemist who discovered several chemical elements (including sodium and potassium) and compounds, invented the miner's safety lamp, and became one of the greatest exponents of the scientific method.

question_text: Sonia Nazario of "Los Angeles Times" was awarded Pulitzer Prize in 2003 for
explanation: Sonia Nazario of "Los Angeles Times" was awarded Pulitzer Prize in 2003 for feature writing. The story was awarded the 2003 Pulitzer Prize for feature writing and later became a book.

question_text: Soil is formed from the parent rock material by
explanation: Soil is formed from the parent rock material by chemical decomposition, physical decomposition and biological decomposition.

question_text: The air we inhale is mixture of gases. Which of the following gases in the mixture is highest in percentage?
explanation: The air we inhale is mixture of gases. Nitrogen of the following gases in the mixture is highest in percentage. Inhaled air is by volume 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen and small amounts include argon, carbon dioxide, neon, helium, and hydrogen.

question_text: Oxford university was founded in
explanation: Oxford university was founded in 1163 AD. The University of Oxford is a collegiate research university in Oxford, England.

question_text: The American General who led the revolt against the British and declared American independence was
explanation: The American General who led the revolt against the British and declared American independence was George Washington.

question_text: Regular meetings of Trusteeship Council (UNO) are held
explanation: Regular meetings of Trusteeship Council (UNO) are held twice a year. The United Nations Trusteeship Council is one of the six principal organs of the United Nations, established to help ensure that trust territories were administered in the best interests of their inhabitants and of international peace and security.

question_text: Radioactive substances can be produced readily in
explanation: Radioactive substances can be produced readily in an atomic pile. Radioactive substances are atoms that decay naturally. They can give off alpha particles, beta particles and gamma radiation. Unlike X-ray sources they cannot be turned off, so their control is more difficult.

question_text: The 2002 Commonwealth Games were held in
explanation: The 2002 Commonwealth Games were held in UK. The 2002 Commonwealth Games, officially known as the XVII Commonwealth Games and commonly known as Manchester 2002 were held in Manchester, England, from 25 July to 4 August 2002.

question_text: Profit made when an asset is sold more than the price at which it was bought is called
explanation: Profit made when an asset is sold more than the price at which it was bought is called capital-gain. Capital gain is the profit one earns on the sale of an asset like stocks, bonds or real estate. It results in capital gain when the selling price of an asset exceeds its purchase price. It is the difference between the selling price (higher) and cost price (lower) of the asset.

question_text: Plorence(Chadwick) is the associated place for which of the following sport?
explanation: Plorence(Chadwick) is the associated place for Skiing.

question_text: The 2012 Olympics Games were held in

question_text: South Africa joined the Commonwealth as 51st member in
explanation: South Africa joined the Commonwealth as 51st member in May 1994. question_text: Recently lead free petrol was introduced in our country because
option_A: they are not needed now as anti-knock agents
option_C: they tower the efficiency of the engine
option_D: to reduce the cost of petrol
explanation: Recently lead free petrol was introduced in our country because they cause less pollution. question_text: Rabindranath Tagore receive Nobel Prize in 1913 in the field of
explanation: Rabindranath Tagore receive Nobel Prize in 1913 in the field of literature. question_text: People who secretly indulge in anti-national or anti-government activities and help the enemy are called
explanation: People who secretly indulge in anti-national or anti-government activities and help the enemy are called Fifth column. explanation: Oxygen was independently discovered by Carl Wilhelm Scheele, in Uppsala, in 1773 or earlier, and Joseph Priestley in Wiltshire, in 1774, but Priestley is often given priority because his work was published first.

explanation: Rise of the Chinese civilization along the banks of Hawang Ho took place in 2205 - 1122 BC. question_text: Steel is more elastic than Rubber because

question_text: Tansen was

option_B: one of the nine gems in the court of Akbar
explanation: Tansen was a great exponent of Indian classical music and one of the nine gems in the court of Akbar. question_text: Ornithology is the
explanation: Ornithology is the study of birds. An ornithologist is someone who studies ornithology the branch of science devoted to birds. Ornithologists study every aspect of birds, including bird songs, flight patterns, physical appearance, and migration patterns.

question_text: Rabindranath Tagore is also known as
explanation: Rabindranath Tagore is also known as Gurudev. He was popularly called as Gurudev and his songs were popularly known as Rabindrasangeet. Two songs from his Rabindrasangit canon are now the national anthems of India and Bangladesh: the Jana Gana Mana and the Amar Shonar Bangla. Rabindranath Tagore was born on May 7, 1861 in a wealthy Brahmin family in Calcutta.

question_text: Raj Kapoor received Dada Saheb Phalke Award in
explanation: Raj Kapoor received Dada Saheb Phalke Award in 1987. The Government of India honoured him with the Padma Bhushan in 1971 and the Dadasaheb Phalke Award in 1987 – the highest award for cinematic excellence in India. In 2001, he was honoured with "Best Director of the Millennium" by Stardust Awards. He was named "Showman of the Millennium" by Star Screen Awards in 2002.

answer: Academy of Motion Pictures, arts and sciences, USA

question_text: Robert Koch worked on
explanation: Robert Koch worked on tuberculosis. German physician Robert Koch was one of the founders of bacteriology. He discovered the anthrax disease cycle and the bacteria responsible for tuberculosis and cholera. He received the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1905 for his research on tuberculosis.

question_text: In Air Force, Air Commodore has one rank higher than
explanation: In Air Force, Air Commodore has one rank higher than Group Captain. Air commodore is a one-star rank and the most junior air officer rank, being immediately senior to group captain and immediately subordinate to air vice-marshal. It has a NATO ranking code of OF-6 and is equivalent to a commodore in the Royal Navy or a brigadier in the British Army or the Royal Marines.

question_text: How much districts are there in Tamil Nadu?
explanation: There are 33 districts in Tamil Nadu.

explanation: There are 981 dynes in one gram weight. Dyne is a CGS unit.

explanation: In big cities like Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Chennai police is headed by a Commissioner of Police. Police commissioners serve their communities by overseeing police departments, either as sworn officers or as civilians selected to sit on a board of police commissioners.

question_text: Indian Institute of Petroleum is located at
explanation: Indian Institute of Petroleum is located at Dehradun. Indian Institute of Petroleum is situated in Dehradun in Uttarakhand state of India. It is established in 1960.

explanation: In UNO, the new members are admitted to the General Assembly on the recommendation of Security Council and two-third of the members of the General Assembly should vote in favour.

question_text: Squadron leader Rakesh Sharma was India's first man to go into space. He was ____ cosmonaut to be in space in the world.
explanation: Squadron leader Rakesh Sharma was India's first man to go into space. He was 139th cosmonaut to be in space in the world. Sharma progressed through numerous levels and in 1984, he was appointed as a squadron leader and pilot in the Indian Air Force. He was selected on 20 September 1982 to become a cosmonaut and go into space as part of a joint program between the Indian Air Force and the Soviet Interkosmos space program.

explanation: Philology is the science of languages. Philology, traditionally, the study of the history of language, including the historical study of literary texts.

question_text: The 2006 World Cup Football Tournament held in
explanation: The 2006 World Cup Football Tournament held in Germany. It was held from 9 June to 9 July 2006 in Germany, which won the right to host the event in July 2000.

question_text: Satellite launching station is located at
explanation: Satellite launching station is located at Sriharikotta (Andhra Pradesh). Satish Dhawan Space Centre (SDSC) or Sriharikota Range (SHAR) is a rocket launch centre operated by the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO). It is located in Sriharikota in Andhra Pradesh. Sriharikota Range was renamed in 2002 after ISRO's former chairman Satish Dhawan.

question_text: The 'Black flag' signifies
explanation: The 'Black flag' signifies protest.

question_text: Study of life in outer space is known as
explanation: Study of life in outer space is known as exobiology. This branch of science deals with nature of possible life forms on other planets. question_text: School of Aviation Medicine (Air Force) is located at
explanation: School of Aviation Medicine (Air Force) is located at Bangalore.

question_text: Recession is
option_A: slowing down of economic activity over a limited period
option_B: period that results from accumulation of unsold goods, owing to fall in demand

explanation: Recession is slowing down of economic activity over a limited period, period that results from accumulation of unsold goods, owing to fall in demand and period during which unemployment may rise and demand and output may fall, leading to slump in trade.

question_text: Sir Thomas Fearnley Cup is awarded to
option_A: amateur athlete, not necessarily an Olympian
option_B: National Olympic Committee for outstanding work
option_C: a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements
answer: a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements
explanation: Sir Thomas Fearnley Cup is awarded to a club or a local sport association for remarkable achievements. Fearnley became Honorary Member of the IOC 1951. In 1950, he founded the Fearnley Cup to honor an amateur sport club or a local amateur sport association based upon meritorious achievement in the service of the Olympic Movement. He originated the Fearnley Olympic Award in connection with the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo. The award is given for outstanding achievements by a Norwegian Olympic participant.

question_text: Pythagoras was first to ____ the universal validity of geometrical theorem.
explanation: Pythagoras was first to prove the universal validity of geometrical theorem. He is known best for the proof of the important Pythagorean theorem, which is about right angle triangles.

question_text: Soil acidity is generally corrected by
explanation: Soil acidity is generally corrected by liming. Soil acidity can be corrected easily by liming the soil, or adding basic materials to neutralize the acid present. The most commonly used liming material is agricultural limestone, the most economical and relatively easy to manage source. The limestone is not very water-soluble, making it easy to handle.

question_text: Oscar Awards were instituted in
explanation: Oscar Awards were instituted in 1929. The 1st Academy Awards ceremony, presented by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), honored the best films of 1927 and 1928 and took place on May 16, 1929, at a private dinner held at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel in Los Angeles, California.

question_text: Small amounts of iodine are necessary in our diet to
option_D: compensate for underactive the thyroid gland
answer: compensate for underactive the thyroid gland
explanation: Small amounts of iodine are necessary in our diet to compensate for underactive the thyroid gland. When blood levels of TSH rise, the thyroid gland uses iodine to make thyroid hormones. However, when your body is low in iodine, it can't make enough of them.

question_text: Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Service is an International Airline of
explanation: Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Service is an International Airline of Australia. Qantas, in full Qantas Airways Limited, Australian airline, the oldest in the English-speaking world, founded in 1920 as Queensland and Northern Territory Aerial Services Ltd. (from which the name Qantas was derived).

question_text: Shaurya Chakra made up of bronze is awarded for
option_A: gallantry in the presence of enemy
option_B: gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy
option_C: most conspicuous bravery for some act of self sacrifice
answer: gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy
explanation: Shaurya Chakra made up of bronze is awarded for gallantry otherwise than in the face of the enemy. The Shaurya Chakra is an Indian military decoration awarded for valour, courageous action or self-sacrifice while not engaged in direct action with the enemy. It may be awarded to civilians as well as military personnel, sometimes posthumously.

question_text: Sushri Lata Dinanath Mangeshkar received Bharath Ratna in
explanation: Sushri Lata Dinanath Mangeshkar received Bharath Ratna in 2001. She is one of the best-known and most respected playback singers in India. She has recorded songs in over a thousand Hindi films and has sung songs in over thirty-six regional Indian languages and foreign languages, though primarily in Marathi, Hindi, and Bengali.

question_text: Taoism is followed in
option_C: China, Taiwan, Nauru, Brunei, Singapore and Vietnam
answer: China, Taiwan, Nauru, Brunei, Singapore and Vietnam
explanation: Taoism is a Chinese philosophy attributed to Lao Tzu which contributed to the folk religion of the people primarily in the rural areas of China and became the official religion of the country under the Tang Dynasty. Taoism is therefore both a philosophy and a religion. Taoism is also known as Daoism.

question_text: The 2005 Wimbledon Women's Singles champion defeated which of the following to win the title?
explanation: The 2005 Wimbledon Women's Singles champion defeated Lindsay Davenport to win the title. It was the longest Wimbledon women's final match in history, lasting two hours and 45 minutes.

question_text: Sheikh Mujibur Rahman is a well known freedom fighter of
explanation: Sheikh Mujibur Rahman is a well known freedom fighter of Bangladesh. He is often called the father of Bengali nation. He served as the first President of Bangladesh and later as the Prime Minister of Bangladesh from 17 April 1971 until his assassination on 15 August 1975. He is considered to be the driving force behind the independence of Bangladesh. He is popularly dubbed with the title of "Bangabandhu" (Bôngobondhu "Friend of Bengal") by the people of Bangladesh. He became a leading figure in and eventually the leader of the Awami League, founded in 1949 as an East Pakistan-based political party in Pakistan.

question_text: Shares with a fixed rate of dividend that entitle their holders to priority payment over those who hold ordinary shares of a company are called
explanation: Shares with a fixed rate of dividend that entitle their holders to priority payment over those who hold ordinary shares of a company are called preference shares. Preference shares are the shares which promise the holder a fixed dividend, whose payment takes priority over that of ordinary share dividends.

question_text: Shankracharya was the founder of
explanation: Shankracharya was the founder of Advaitic philosophy. He was an early 8th century Indian philosopher and theologian who consolidated the doctrine of Advaita Vedanta. He is credited with unifying and establishing the main currents of thought in Hinduism.

question_text: Sculpture flourished during
explanation: Sculpture flourished during Indus valley civilization. People from this civilisation created sculpture, seals, pottery, and jewellery from materials, such as terracotta, metal, and stone.

question_text: Penicillin is widely used as
explanation: Penicillin is widely used as an antibiotic. Penicillins are a group of antibacterial drugs that attack a wide range of bacteria. They were the first drugs of this type that doctors used. The discovery and manufacture of penicillins have changed the face of medicine, as these drugs have saved millions of lives.

question_text: Socrates was the wisest man of the ancient world and developed the method of enquiry and instruction, belonged to
explanation: Socrates was the wisest man of the ancient world and developed the method of enquiry and instruction, belonged to Athens.
